package dev.cajeta.unit;

/**
 * An argument matcher — the predicate side of Mockito-style stubbing and
 * verification. A matcher answers "does this recorded argument satisfy me?"
 * against a single argument boxed as an `Object`.
 *
 * Matchers are the AoT analogue of Mockito's `any()/eq()/argThat()`: there is no
 * runtime proxy, so a hand-written mock boxes each argument into an `Object[]`
 * and the engine matches stub/verify rules against those boxes. Build matchers
 * with {@Link ArgMatchers}; an empty matcher set means "match any arguments".
 *
 * Implementations must not rely on `instanceof` (unreliable on boxed primitives
 * in the current toolchain) — compare via `Object` equality (which dispatches
 * the value-based `hash()` of box types) or a downcast inside an `argThat`
 * predicate.
 *
 * `Matcher` is a **base class**, not an interface, on purpose: a factory that
 * returns an *interface* type by ownership transfer (`#`) and dispatches through
 * it produces a bad vtable pointer in the current toolchain (interface
 * fat-pointer instantiation is still maturing). A base class with virtual
 * `matches(...)` — the same shape as the tour's `DemoClass` — dispatches
 * correctly, including from a `#`-returning factory and through a `Matcher[]`.
 * The default `matches(...)` returns false; every real matcher overrides it.
 */
public class Matcher {
    /** Whether `arg` (a boxed argument, possibly null) satisfies this matcher. */
    public boolean matches(Object arg) {
        return false;
    }
}
